[{"id":"VH984644","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VH984642.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The depiction of the Soviet Union in the images is best explained as illustrating which of the following developments in late-twentieth-century communist states?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH984644_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\"><span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">Image 1</span></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<p class=\"title_line passage-title\">VLADIMIR KANDELAKI, SOVIET ARTIST, <span class=\"font_style:italic formatted_text\">HOUSE OF CARDS</span>, PAINTING, 1986</p>\n</div>\n<img alt=\"The figure presents a political cartoon titled “House of Cards” that depicts a military parade in Red Square, Moscow. The Kremlin is depicted as being constructed of playing cards of various suits. In front of the representation of the Kremlin is a platform that is supported by playing cards. Numerous Soviet military and political leaders are standing on top of the platform. The Soviet leaders are saluting troops in three tanks bearing Soviet flags below the platform. Immediately in front of the tanks is a platform draped in red that contains a large golden embroidered symbol of the Soviet emblem and a motorcycle equipped with a sidecar carrying two soldiers and a Soviet flag. Directly in front of those figures is a marching band and a large globe with a ribbon containing an inscription written in Russian. The globe is erected on a large red platform.\" height=\"338\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/507/VH984642.g05.png\" width=\"450\" /><span class=\"mandatory_credit_line\">© 2019 Artists Rights Society (ARS), New York / GCA, Tbilisi</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\"><span class=\"font_style:italic formatted_text\">The image is a parody of the regular military parades staged by the Soviet Communist Party in Red Square, Moscow.</span></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\"><span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">Image 2</span></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<p class=\"title_line passage-title\">MARAT VALIAKHMETOV, SOVIET ARTIST, “PARADE,” CARTOON PUBLISHED IN A SOVIET NEWSPAPER, 1989</p>\n</div>\n<img alt=\"The figure presents a political cartoon titled “Parade” that shows a mock parade in front of the Kremlin in Red Square, Moscow. Large groups of people are standing directly in front of the Kremlin walls. Numerous balloons are being released into the sky above the Kremlin. Nine large trucks are shown parading past the crowds. Each truck has a label on its side that is one of the following 3 words in Russian: milk, bread, or meat.\" height=\"381\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/507/VH984642.g03.png\" width=\"500\" /></div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\"><span class=\"font_style:italic formatted_text\">The cartoon is a parody of Soviet military parades, with food trucks instead of tanks and military equipment. The trucks carry labels saying “BREAD,” “MILK,” and “MEAT”—all items for which the Soviet Union was experiencing frequent consumer shortages.</span></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Increasing instances of using force to quell political protests</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Rising ethnic nationalism</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Increasing political instability because of military coups</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Rising public discontent</p>"],"answer":3}]